                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Culbryz wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Is it ganking if you are the same level as your target but you attack them while they are fighting a mob?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
In my opinion only - Yes this is ganking.
<br />

<br />
I'm happy to say I've only done this once - and actually regret it.  Myself, I have been ganked at least half a dozen times - and escaped from attempt to kill me in this fashion an equal number.  Yesterday on my run to the Badlands, I could've ganked at least 5 alliance.  I chose not to.  This was partially out of self interest as I knew my position / class / level would likely be reported in local defense and would then have to deal with more opposition en-route to my destination.
<br />

<br />
A one-time gank is to be expected in PvP.  You or the enemy is traveling or questing along, and decides to take down a target of opportunity.  While it would be more "honorable" to wait for them to finish killing the mob they are on then rest and heal up, it is also stupid.
<br />

<br />
Are there times where you should think hard prior to ganking?  Yes, in my opinion.  Case in point:  Stranglethorn Jungle.  There's a dwarf camp (npc's green to both factions) that hand out the same quests to both Alliance and Horde.  Yesterday on Mal`Ganis, we had an uneasy truce in place between factions in that area.  Both alliance and horde were coming and going from the quest npcs, and killing mobs within sight of each other throughout the area.
<br />

<br />
I was happy to see this as it was the first time I've been around more than 1 or 2 alliance who didn't attempt to kill me on sight.  Levels were ranging from high 20s to about 40.
<br />

<br />
That said - after about an hour I was ganked by a mage about 5 levels my senior.  I wasn't corpse camped - but possibly only because I reported it in local defense and some other horde killed him before I could even CR.  Continued to quest in the area another hour without incident.
<br />

<br />
I have hope that in quest areas like this - the factions can agree to permit each other the opportunity to quest.  On a PvP server, this level of cooperation is to a degree, necessary - if both factions want to quest and level up.
<br />

<br />
Of greater concern is the practice of "griefing".  I define this as:  intentionally seeking out opposing faction to gank.  Corpse camping.  Entering opposing faction quest areas (whether it be of same or lower level) with no intent on doing anything other than disturbing the opposing faction's PvE experience.
<br />

<br />
Griefing is something I won't do.  Why?  I don't see it as fun, and I'd rather spend my time upgrading my abilities, equipment, and level as opposed to making it hard for others to do the same.  I've seen a lot of alliance griefing - most notably in Hillsbrad by level 30s against level 20s.  I will corpse camp griefers if they keep coming back - cause that's the only way to stop them.
<br />

<br />
Mirabelle - 33 Foresaken Rogue - Mal`Ganis</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
